content.description: Starts on the thin crack on the right side of the west face of the crag. Crack opens up to jammable size after about 10 feet. It gets a little ledgy for a bit then ends at the same spot as the route to the left.
content.protection: A small nut for the start, a couple of pieces in the .5-1.5'' range. Chain on top.

content.description:
The physical crux is low, just off the ground as you work your way into the crack system.  The mental crux is definitely clipping the chain at the top.  Work a ledge system in from the left to get to the finger crack, which starts about 12 feet up.  Be wary of a few questionable rock chunks up high. 

  There is a plethora of possibilities for climbs here, and at least one anchor on top.
content.protection: 0.3 to #3 (save a 0.5 for the last placement before anchor); chain anchor at top.
content.location: This is the middle of three cracks on the NW side of the formation.  You can't miss it--it's the one with "Token STM" spray-painted over the bottom section.

content.description: This small crag is on the back side of a roadside boulder, giving it about a 10 second approach.  Not the most aesthetic or solid, but it's great if you only have a few minutes and want to get a climb in.
